    The Route End service ends a routing dialogue. This service is bi-directional (i.e., it may be invoked by the application or the switch). The application can use the Route End service when it cannot provide a route for a call. Typically this can occurs if: - The application receives a valid routing request for a call without sufficient call information and it cannot determine a routing destination. - The application has already provided all available destinations for a call and no more alternate destinations are available. - The application does not have access to a database necessary to route the call. The switch uses the Route End service when it ends a routing dialogue. Typically, this can occurs if: - The call associated with the routing cross reference identifier has been successfully routed. This may occur when the application has sent a Route Select service request and the switch has successfully routed the call. - The calling party has abandoned a call associated with the routing cross reference identifier. - The switch timeout for a route request response has expired. This may occur if the application did not respond to a Route Request service within a switch defined period. - The switch has ended a routing dialogue due to internal resource problems. There areno servcie completion conditions for this service.
